```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    Sensor -> ChargeAmplifier -> LowPassFilter -> OutputStage -> ADC -> AntiAliasingFilter -> Microcontroller;

    subgraph cluster_0 {
        label="Analog Front End";
        Sensor;
        ChargeAmplifier;
        LowPassFilter;
        OutputStage;
    }

    subgraph cluster_1 {
        label="Digital Processing";
        ADC;
        AntiAliasingFilter;
        Microcontroller;
    }
}
```

```Explanations
Sensor:
- The piezoelectric accelerometer transduces mechanical vibrations into an electrical charge signal proportional to the acceleration experienced. With the specified sensitivity of 100 pC/g, it converts the low-frequency vibration into a measurable electrical charge.

Charge Amplifier:
- This block converts the charge output from the piezoelectric sensor into a voltage. It has very high input impedance to collect the charge efficiently without leakage and low output impedance to drive subsequent stages. The gain of the charge amplifier is set to produce the required 1 V peak-to-peak output for the given peak-to-peak charge generated by the sensor.

Low Pass Filter:
- A low pass filter (LPF) is employed to attenuate unwanted high-frequency noise and to ensure the low-frequency response of the system is 3 dB down at 0.25 Hz. This filter also conditions the signal to be within the desired frequency range of interest, protecting against aliasing before digitization.

Output Stage:
- The output stage buffers the conditioned analog signal and may provide additional voltage scaling to match the input range of an ADC. This stage ensures that the system's offset is kept below 10 mV and drives the signal to the ADC without distortion.

ADC:
- The analog-to-digital converter digitizes the analog signal from the output stage. The resolution and sampling rate of the ADC are chosen based on the Nyquist criterion, considering the maximum frequency of interest.

Anti-Aliasing Filter:
- Placed immediately before the ADC, the anti-aliasing filter removes frequencies above half the sampling rate of the ADC to prevent aliasing, which can corrupt the digital representation of the analog signal.

Microcontroller:
- The microcontroller manages the digital signal processing tasks, including data storage, calibration, user interface, and communication. It can also implement additional digital filtering or analysis algorithms on the digitized vibration data.
```

